5000|$|The {{preferred}} habitat {{theory is}} {{a variant of}} the liquidity premium theory, and states that in addition to interest rate expectations, investors have distinct investment horizons and require a meaningful premium to buy bonds with maturities outside their [...] "preferred" [...] maturity, or habitat. Proponents of this theory believe that short-term investors are more prevalent in the fixed-income market, and therefore longer-term rates tend to be higher than <b>short-term</b> <b>rates,</b> for the most part, but <b>short-term</b> <b>rates</b> can be higher than long-term rates occasionally. This theory is consistent with both the persistence of the normal yield curve shape and the tendency of the yield curve to shift up and down while retaining its shape.|$|E
